\(1.\) Parallel Coordinates

\((a)\) Draw a parallel coordinates plot of the data in ManhattanCDResults.csv in the data folder on CourseWorks. (Original data source and additional information about the data can be found here: https://cbcny.org/research/nyc-resident-feedback-survey-community-district-results). Your plot should have one line for each of the twelve Manhattan community districts in the dataset.

library(GGally)
mydata <- read.csv(file="c:/Users/Mingyang/Desktop/ManhattanCDResults.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")


mydata = mydata[,-2]
makenumber<- function(x){
  removesing<-sub("%", "", x)
  number=as.numeric(removesing)/100
}
for (col in colnames(mydata[,-1])){

    mydata[col] = sapply(mydata[col], makenumber)
  
}
MyData2=t(mydata)
MyData2=MyData2[-1,]
index=c('cd1','cd2','cd3','cd4','cd5','cd6','cd7','cd8','cd9','cd10','cd11','cd12')
index=as.vector(index)


MyData3=as.data.frame(MyData2)
indx <- sapply(MyData3, is.factor)
MyData3[indx] <- lapply(MyData3[indx], function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x)))
MyData3=cbind(MyData3,index)
MyData3=MyData3[,c(46,1:45)]
ggparcoord(MyData3,columns=c(2:46), groupColumn = "index",scale = "globalminmax")

\((b)\) Do there appear to be greater differences across indicators or across community districts? (In other words, are Manhattan community districts more alike or more different in how their citizens express their satisfaction with city life?

There appear to be greater differences across different indicators. As we can see from the plots, for all the community, they pretty much follow the same trend. Altough we can see a bit difference between lines for example at v1, this is not as dominant as the difference caused by indicators such as v8, v24.

\(2.\) Mosaic Plots

Using the Death2015.txt data from the previous assignment, create a mosaic plot to identify whether Age is associated with Place of Death. Include only the top four Age categories. Treat Age as the independent variable and Place of Death as the dependent variable. (Hint: the dependent variable should be the last cut and it should be horizontal.) The labeling should be clear enough to identify whats what, that is, good enough, not perfect. Do the variables appear to be associated? Describe briefly.

library(vcd)
library(grid)
library(dplyr)
death = read.table('c:/Users/Mingyang/Desktop/Death2015.txt', nrows = 6896, header = TRUE, sep = "\t")
death %>% 
  group_by(death$Ten.Year.Age.Groups) %>%
  summarise(no_rows = length(death$Ten.Year.Age.Groups))
## # A tibble: 12 x 2
##    `death$Ten.Year.Age.Groups` no_rows
##    <fct>                         <int>
##  1 < 1 year                       6896
##  2 1-4 years                      6896
##  3 15-24 years                    6896
##  4 25-34 years                    6896
##  5 35-44 years                    6896
##  6 45-54 years                    6896
##  7 5-14 years                     6896
##  8 55-64 years                    6896
##  9 65-74 years                    6896
## 10 75-84 years                    6896
## 11 85+ years                      6896
## 12 Not Stated                     6896
data1 = death %>% group_by(`Ten.Year.Age.Groups`,`Place.of.Death`) %>%summarize(Freq=n())
top4 = levels(death$Ten.Year.Age.Groups)[1:4]
data1=data1[is.element(data1$Ten.Year.Age.Groups,top4),]
Age = factor(data1$Ten.Year.Age.Groups, levels = top4)
vcd::mosaic(data1$Place.of.Death ~ Age, data1,rot_labels = c(90, 0, 90, 0))

from the plot, we can see that the proportion within each age group is not the same. We can observe that they are uncorrelated.

\(3.\) Time Series

\((a)\) Use the tidyquant package to collect stock information on four stocks of your choosing. Create a line chart showing the closing price of the four stocks on the same graph, employing a different color for each stock.

library(tidyquant)
library(tidyverse)
stockname=c("MSFT", "AAPL", "GS","JPM")
stock = tq_get(stockname, get = "stock.prices")
ggplot(stock, aes(date, close, color = symbol)) + geom_line()+ggtitle("stock price plot")

\((b)\) Transform the data so each stock begins at 100 and replot. Do you learn anything new that wasnt visible in part (a)?

stock= stock %>% group_by(symbol) 
tidystock=stock%>%mutate(standardprice = 100*close/close[1]) %>% ungroup()
ggplot(tidystock, aes(date, standardprice, color = symbol)) + geom_line()+ggtitle("stock price plot")

Yes, this makes the relative growth more obvious. In parta, due to the difference in initial price, the growth of the stock price is not very abvious throughout the time horizon. After standardising the beginning price, the relative growth rate now is much more obvious. AAPL have the largest growth.

\(4.\) Missing Data

For this question, explore the New York State Feb 2017 snow accumulation dataset available in the data folder on CourseWorks: NY-snowfall-201702.csv. The original data source is here: https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/snow-and-ice/daily-snow/

\((a)\) Show missing patterns graphically.

MyData4 <- read.csv(file="c:/Users/Mingyang/Desktop/NY-snowfall-201702.csv", header=TRUE,skip=1, na.strings="M",check.name=FALSE,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
snow=MyData4%>% select(`Feb 1`:`Feb 28`)%>%mutate_all(funs(ifelse(.=="T",.005,.)%>% as.numeric()))
library(mi)
x <- missing_data.frame(snow)
image(x)

\((b)\) Is the percent of missing values consistent across days of the month, or is there variety?

percentage_of_missingdata=colSums(is.na(snow))/349
plot(percentage_of_missingdata,type="o")

It is not consistent across days of the month. We can see that certain dates will have a spike in the amount of missing data. However, this is only one month of data. The conclusion we draw here will not be very trustworthy.

\((c)\) Is the percent of missing values consistent across collection stations, or is there variety?

percentage_of_missingdata=rowSums(is.na(snow))/28
plot(percentage_of_missingdata)

It is not consistent, we can see that certain station have a very low missing data while others have close to 1. It is obvious from the plot this is not consistent.

\((d)\) Is the daily average snowfall correlated with the daily missing values percent? On the basis of these results, what is your assessment of the reliability of the data to capture true snowfall patterns? In other words, based on what youve discovered, do you think that the missing data is highly problematic, or not?

percentage_of_missingdata=colSums(is.na(snow))/349
a=na.omit(snow)
avgsnowfall=colSums(a)/colSums(is.na(snow))

plot(avgsnowfall,percentage_of_missingdata)

This is not causing a lot of trouble. Most of the high percentage of missing data is concentrate on the low avgsnowfall which we do not care so much as compared to days with high snow fall.
